article.description:
With the top seed in the Eastern
Conference up for grabs, the New Jersey Nets got what they needed
against injury-riddled Toronto, a victory and a couple of laughs.
article.headline: New Jersey now a half-game up on idle Detroit
article.linkText: Nets take lead in East by abusing hurting Raptors
article.story:
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- With the top seed in the Eastern Conference up for grabs, the New Jersey Nets got what they needed against injury-riddled Toronto, a victory and a couple of laughs. Richard Jefferson scored 21 points and banked in a 3-pointer from mid-court at the end of the third quarter to lighten the mood as the Nets opened a half-game lead over idle Detroit in the conference race with a 94-86 victory Saturday night. New Jersey has two games left in the regular season, one less than the Pistons. ''It was a good win against a team decimated by injuries,'' Nets coach Byron Scott said. ''I knew they were going to come out and play hard.'' Fortunately for the Nets, the Raptors had only seven players available, and that wasn't even close to being enough on a night the Nets built a 23-point second-half lead and coasted home. ''I'm proud of the way we went out there and played,'' Toronto's Morris Peterson said after scoring 22 points in 46 minutes. ''I think that shows the character of this team. We played with seven guys and had a great first quarter, they just had a lot more players than we did and we couldn't stay with them.'' Kenyon Martin added 19 points and nine rebounds, and Jason Kidd had 17 points and eight assists for New Jersey, which also increased its lead in the Atlantic Division to 1½ games over idle Philadelphia. This was an important game for the Nets, who were returning home after defeats at Atlanta and Chicago. ''If we were thinking about last night's game, it would have affected today's game,'' Martin said. ''We just got to go out and play. We know what's at stake for the playoffs. The regular season is over. There is no time for ups and downs. You've got to play well. We have no choice.'' Rafer Alston scored 19 for Toronto, which found out minutes before the tipoff that starting guard Alvin Williams was out with an ankle injury. Williams put on his uniform and sat on the bench so the Raptors had the league minimum of eight dressed players. However, all he could do was watch Toronto lose its sixth in a row in a season in which it has set an NBA record for games lost to injury. Toronto also is missing Vince Carter (ankle), Antonio Davis (groin), Eric Montross (foot), Lamond Murray (foot) Hakeem Olajuwon (back), Maceo Baston (ankle), Lindsay Hunter (back) and Voshon Lenard (knee). The Raptors, also playing their second game in two nights, led by as many as five points in the first quarter, the last time at 26-21 on a jumper by Chris Jefferies with just more than a minute to go. But Martin hit two free throws and Kidd hit a 3-pointer with less than a second to go to tie the game. Jefferson gave New Jersey the lead for good with a layup in the opening seconds of the second quarter, and Kidd gave the Nets breathing room late in the period by hitting a 3-pointer and a layup for a 58-45 halftime edge. Jefferson added to Toronto's frustration with his 3-pointer at the end of the third quarter. He tight-roped the sidelines and launched an off-balance shot that hit glass and banked in for an 84-65 lead. Even the videotape review didn't help the Raptors, who made the score respectable by limiting New Jersey to 10 points in the fourth quarter. ''We were making a run at the end of the quarter, and that shot hurt us,'' said Alston, who couldn't help but laugh thinking about it. Game notes
The Nets swept the four-game season series with Toronto for the first time. ... Toronto is 1-16 in the second game of back-to-back games. ... Nets center Dikembe Mutombo, getting back into shape after missing most of the season with a wrist injury, had four points and 11 rebounds. Coach Byron Scott said Mutombo will replace Jason Collins in the starting lineup soon. ... The game had some testy moments. Alston and Collins shoved each other in the third quarter after a Toronto basket. Collins appeared to hit Alston in the face on the layup. Both got technical fouls. Martin and Rodney Rogers also picked up technicals for New Jersey. ... New Jersey is 33-7 at home.
